@database DLGGuide.Guide
@$VER: DLGGuide  by Don Grout  v2.32  03-May-94

@node main "DLGGuide  by Don Grout  v2.32  03-May-94"

This is a simple utility that converts DLG's BBS message file into an
AmigaGuide series of files.  The following is a description of how to use the
program.  This program is released to the public domain, just remember where
it came from.

@{" What's New " link "New"}    What's new since the last version.
@{" Requirements " link "Requirements"}  What you need to run DLGGuide.
@{" Parameters " link "Parameters"}    Command Line and Tool Type parameters.
@{" Converting " link "Converting"}    Converting a text file to AmigaGuide format.
@{" Using Guide " link "Using"}   Using DLGMsgs.Guide
@{" Source Code " link "DLGGuide.c/main"}   The C source code.
@{" File Listing " link "Files"}  A listing of all files in this archive.
@{" History " link "History"}       A revision history of DLGGuide.
@{" Conclusion " link "Conclusion"}    In Conclusion.
@endnode

@node New "DLGGuide - What's New"

The last two minor updates have removed case sensitivity in searching the
'DLGGuide.MsgAreas' file and changed the '-' symbol in the table of contents
to a button to delete message area files that you have already read.

First of all, this document is now in AmigaGuide format.

When executed from Workbench, Tool Types can be specified and a proper window
is opened.

A new parameter, @{"WINDOW" link "Parameters"}, will specify the type and size of window to open.

Also now supported is the Locale if you have Workbench 2.1 or greater.

Also with the date, there was a programming hack to change 'Today' dates to
proper 'DD-MMM-YY' dates, but now it's fixed and it supports the Locale.

Finally, when you get to the end of reading a Message Area, you can press
'Browse >' to return to the Contents.


See Also:  @{" History " link "History"}
@endnode

@node Requirements "DLGGuide - Requirements"

This utility, as stated, converts the text file @{"DLGMsgs.txt" link "DLGMsgs.txt"} into a format
for AmigaGuide.

Therefore this utility requires that you:
 a) use a BBS that gathers mail in DLG Telepro's format (although you can
    probably customize the program for other BBS's)
 b) that you have a copy of AmigaGuide (by Commodore) for reading the
    converted file.  You can still read the converted files with a plain old
    text reader, but then you would miss out on all the benefits of
    AmigaGuide.

It is recommended that you turn 'Thread Mode' ON in the DLG BBS before
bundling mail.  This will help group any messages that receive replies
together.
@endnode

@node Parameters "DLGGuide - Parameters"

The following parameters can be either specified on the Command Line (if
executed from a Shell), in the Tool Types (if executed from the Workbench),
and/or saved in the file ENV:DLGGuide.

Parameters saved in the file ENV:DLGGuide will be considered the default.  If
you specify parameters on the Command Line or in the Tool Types, they will
override those in ENV:DLGGuide.


Required Parameters
-------------------
FILE=<inputfile>   The path and filename of your @{"DLGMsgs.txt" link "DLGMsgs.txt"} file to convert.


Optional Parameters
-------------------
PATH=<outputpath>  The path to where you want your output AmigaGuide files to
                   go.  If not specified, they will go to your current
                   directory.
NOPATH             This option, if specified, will cancel out the placement of
                   the path in the output AmigaGuide files.
MSGFILE=<msgfile>  The path and filename of a list of message areas and the
                   number of each area.  Refer to the enclosed sample file
                   @{"DLGGuide.MsgAreas" link "DLGGuide.MsgAreas/main"} for the BBS that I use.
WINDOW=<winspec>   Specify the type of window to use for progress messages
                   while converting your messages.  When run from the CLI, no
                   window is created except if you use this parameter.
                   The default, when run from the Workbench, is
                   CON:10/10/620/180/DLGGuide.


CLI Example:
DLGGuide FILE=RAM:@{"DLGMsgs.txt" link "DLGMsgs.txt"} PATH=MSG: MSGFILE=bin:@{"DLGGuide.MsgAreas" link "DLGGuide.MsgAreas/main"}
@endnode

@node Converting "DLGGuide - Converting the Text File"

To convert your messages text file to AmigaGuide format, just execute DLGGuide
either from the CLI or the Workbench with the minimum @{"parameters" link "Parameters"} specified.

Once the program has started running, the current message area that's being
worked on will be displayed.

After you've converted your @{"DLGMsgs.txt" link "DLGMsgs.txt"}, at the output path that you
specified (if specified) or in the current directory, you will find the main
file, 'DLGMsgs.Guide', and files for each message area and their indexes.
@endnode

@node Using "DLGGuide - Using DLGMsgs.Guide"

After you load the file 'DLGMsgs.Guide' into AmigaGuide, you will get the
table of contents.  This lists the number of subjects in each message area
and the name of the message area.  The titlebar displays the date and time
of your @{"DLGMsgs.txt" link "DLGMsgs.txt"} file.  Clicking on the number of subjects will give an
index of all the subject's discussed in that message area.  You can click on
a subject to read that subject.  Back at the table of contents, you can
click on the message area to start reading the first message in that area.
Once you are finised reading a message area, click on the '-' button to delete
those message area files.

When reading a subject, you can 'Browse' forward or backward to jump to the
respective subject.  Pressing 'Contents' will return you to the table of
contents.  Pressing 'Index' will bring up a new window with the index for the
current message area.  Pressing '[Subject]' will also bring up the index in
the current window at about the current message number.
@endnode

